                <div class="tabpanel">
					<a href="/img/pages/account/home-client.webp" target="_blank"><img src="/img/pages/account/home-client.webp" alt="Staking Dashboard - client" width="100%"></a>
				</div>
            </div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="egrid egrid-2 mt-100 separator-horizontal separator-before" style="padding-top:100px">
		<div>
			<h2>Privacy-focused dashboard for your staking environment</h2>
			<ul>
				
				<li>You can update any data on the dashbaord through UI or API. You can automatically update validators state, servers state, send alerts and many more.</li>
				<li>Stakers.space can monitor server data you send (SSD, RAM, SWAP etc. usage) and alert you on reaching a critical value.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
		<div>
			<a href="/img/pages/account/ss-api.svg" target="_blank"><img src="/img/pages/account/ss-api.svg" alt="Staking Dashboard - API" width="100%" height="400px"></a>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="egrid egrid-2 mt-100 separator-horizontal separator-before" style="padding-top:100px">
		<div>
			<h2>Senstitive data with browser-side encryption</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Stakers.space keeps data in a privacy-focused way. All sensitive data are client-side encrypted. Encryption is processed in the browser - server side hold data in encrypted form.</li>
				<li>As you can share individual validator instances with clients, each validator instance can be encrypted with a custom passowrd.</li>
				<li>No black hole, Stakers.space is <a href="https://github.com/Stakers-space/Web" target="_blank">open-sourced</a>.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
		<div>
			<div class="tabselector">
                <nav class="egrid egrid-2">
                   	<button class="tab" data-tabpanel="1" type="button">Schema</button>
                    <button class="tab selected" data-tabpanel="2" type="button">Database view</button>
                </nav>
                <div class="tabpanel">
					
				</div>
                <div class="tabpanel selected">
					<a href="/img/pages/account/home-client.webp" target="_blank"><img src="/img/pages/account/db-encryption.webp" alt="Staking Dashboard - client" width="100%"></a>
				</div>
            </div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="mt-100 separator-horizontal separator-before" style="padding-top:50px">
		<h2 class="text-center">Sample Features</h2>
		<section class="egrid egrid-2"  style="padding-top:50px">
			<div>
				<h2>Validators monitoring</h2>
			</div>
			<div class="tabselector">
				<nav class="egrid egrid-2">
					<button class="tab selected" data-tabpanel="1" type="button">Via Stakers.space</button>
					<button class="tab" data-tabpanel="2" type="button">Via Own server</button>
				</nav>
				<div class="tabpanel selected">
					<p>You just load all your validator keys to the dashboard either from the deposit file or place your pubkey indexes. Stakers.space monitor all the validatorys for you. All these data are kept in RAM memmory only. However, There's still a link between monitored pubkeys and your account.</p>   
				</div>
				<div class="tabpanel">
					<p>You install a simple script from Github On your machine that monitors all your validator keys. On any issues detection, the script triggers an alert on the dashboard with additional information and email alert, if enabled. As all pubkeys are kept by your server, Stakers.space is not familiar with your public keys not number of validators you operate.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
		<section class="egrid egrid-2"  style="padding-top:50px">
			<div>
				<h2>Server resources monitoring</h2>
				<p>See your SSD, RAM and SWAP usage right at Stakers.space dashboard. Set alerts based on triggers.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<a href="/img/pages/account/server-resources.webp" target="_blank"><img src="/img/pages/account/server-resources.webp" alt="Staking Dashboard - Server resources" width="100%"></a>
